text: Wheat thrives in temperate zones, preferring cool, moist weather during its vegetative growth phase and warm, dry weather for ripening. The optimal temperature range for its entire life cycle is between 10–25°C. For germination, the ideal temperature is 20–25°C. During the crucial tillering stage (formation of side shoots), cooler temperatures of 16–20°C are beneficial

. High temperatures above 32°C during flowering and grain-filling can drastically reduce yields, a phenomenon known as 'terminal heat'. Wheat is a long-day plant, requiring bright, sunny days for optimal grain development. It can grow with annual rainfall ranging from 30 cm to 100 cm, but an evenly distributed 45-65 cm is considered ideal for rainfed crops. The most critical stages for water are Crown Root Initiation (CRI), flowering, and grain-filling.

Wheat grows best in well-drained, fertile loamy or clay-loam soils that have good structure and moderate water-holding capacity. In India, it is extensively cultivated on the alluvial soils of the Indo-Gangetic plains and the black cotton soils (Vertisols) of the Deccan plateau. The ideal soil pH is in the neutral range of 6.0 to 7.5. The crop is sensitive to high salinity and acidity (pH < 5.5)

.0 to 7.5. The crop is sensitive to high salinity and acidity (pH < 5.5). Proper soil preparation is key for good germination and stand establishment; the field should be ploughed and harrowed to create a fine, firm, and moist seedbed free of clods. Conservation tillage practices like zero-tillage are also increasingly adopted to conserve soil moisture and reduce costs.

Fertilizer requirements for wheat vary based on soil tests, crop variety, and irrigation availability. A general recommendation for irrigated wheat is 120-150 kg/ha of Nitrogen (N), 60 kg/ha of Phosphorus (P₂O₅), and 40 kg/ha of Potassium (K₂O). Nitrogen is vital for vegetative growth and grain protein content and is often applied in 2-3 split doses (at sowing, first irrigation, and booting stage)

. Phosphorus is crucial for root development and energy transfer, while Potassium aids in straw strength and disease resistance; both are typically applied as a basal dose. In many regions, micronutrients like Zinc (Zn) and Sulphur (S) are also important. A common recommendation is to apply 25 kg/ha of zinc sulphate in deficient soils.

Wheat is susceptible to several diseases and pests. Key fungal diseases include: Rusts (Yellow/Stripe, Brown/Leaf, and Black/Stem rust), which appear as colored pustules and can cause severe yield loss; Loose Smut, which turns grains into black powder; and Karnal Bunt, which imparts a fishy smell to the grain and is a major quarantine concern. Common insect pests include Aphids, which suck sap and transmit viruses, and Termites, which damage roots in dry conditions

. Integrated Pest Management (IPM) is the recommended approach for control. This includes cultivating resistant varieties (the most economical method), seed treatment with fungicides (for loose smut), timely application of recommended fungicides (e.g., Propiconazole for rusts), proper crop rotation, and regular field monitoring to take action at the earliest stage of infestation.

Wheat is a global staple food. Its primary use is for making flour, which is processed into a vast array of products. High-protein hard wheat is used for bread, while low-protein soft wheat is for biscuits, cakes, and pastries. Durum wheat is specifically used for pasta and semolina (suji). In India, it is the main ingredient for chapati/roti. Besides human food, lower-grade wheat and milling by-products (like bran) are a significant component of animal feed

. Industrially, wheat is used to produce starch, malt for brewing, and biofuels like ethanol. Globally, China is the largest producer, followed by India. In India, the top producing states are Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Punjab, and Haryana. It is a cornerstone of India's food security and public distribution system (PDS).

Rice is a tropical and subtropical plant that requires a hot and humid climate, making it a primary Kharif crop in India. It demands an average temperature of 21°C to 37°C for its entire life cycle. High humidity and prolonged sunshine are essential, especially during the reproductive phase. A key requirement is abundant water, with annual rainfall between 150 cm and 300 cm being optimal. In areas with less rainfall, cultivation depends heavily on irrigation

. In areas with less rainfall, cultivation depends heavily on irrigation. The crop is grown in submerged conditions, and its water needs are highest during the vegetative growth period. Temperatures below 20°C can affect tillering, while temperatures above 35°C can cause poor grain filling and sterility.

Rice is best suited for soils with high water-retention capacity. Deep clayey and loamy soils are considered ideal. The soil should be able to hold water and, for transplanted rice, it must be 'puddled'. Puddling is the process of ploughing the land in standing water, which creates an impervious layer below the surface, reducing deep water percolation and controlling weeds. The ideal soil pH is slightly acidic, ranging from 5.5 to 6.5
. The ideal soil pH is slightly acidic, ranging from 5.5 to 6.5. Rice can tolerate more acidic soils than most other crops but is sensitive to salinity and alkalinity.

Rice is a nutrient-intensive crop. Fertilizer recommendations depend on the variety (hybrids require more) and soil fertility status. A general dose for high-yielding varieties is 100-120 kg/ha of Nitrogen (N), 50-60 kg/ha of Phosphorus (P₂O₅), and 40-50 kg/ha of Potassium (K₂O). Nitrogen is critical for vegetative growth and is applied in 2-3 split doses (basal, active tillering, and panicle initiation) for better efficiency

. Phosphorus and Potassium are vital for root development and grain quality, respectively, and are usually applied as a basal dose. Zinc deficiency is a common disorder in rice fields, leading to 'Khaira disease', which can be corrected by applying zinc sulphate.

Rice faces threats from numerous diseases and pests. Key diseases include: Rice Blast, which causes spindle-shaped lesions on leaves; Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB), causing wilting and leaf drying; and Brown Spot, which affects leaves and grains. Major pests are the Yellow Stem Borer, whose larvae cause 'dead heart' and 'white earhead', and the Brown Planthopper (BPH), which sucks sap leading to 'hopper burn'. Integrated Pest Management (IPM) is crucial

. Integrated Pest Management (IPM) is crucial. This involves using resistant varieties, maintaining optimal plant spacing for air circulation, effective water management, encouraging natural predators, and need-based, judicious application of recommended pesticides.

Rice is the staple food for over half the world's population. It's primarily consumed as boiled or steamed grain. It is also processed into rice flour, flakes (poha), puffed rice (murmura), noodles, and beverages like rice wine. By-products like rice bran are used to extract edible oil, and the husk is used as fuel or in construction materials. China and India are the world's top two producers. India is also a leading global exporter, famous for its aromatic Basmati rice
. India is also a leading global exporter, famous for its aromatic Basmati rice. The major rice-producing states in India are West Bengal, Uttar Pradesh, Punjab, Andhra Pradesh, and Tamil Nadu.

Maize, known as the 'Queen of Cereals', is a warm-weather crop. It requires temperatures between 21°C and 27°C for optimal growth, with abundant sunshine. It is very sensitive to frost at all stages of its life. While it can grow with 50-100 cm of well-distributed rainfall, it is highly susceptible to both drought and waterlogging. The most critical period for water is the 'tasseling' and 'silking' (flowering) stage, where moisture stress can severely impact pollination and grain formation
. In India, maize is uniquely grown across three seasons: Kharif (monsoon), Rabi (winter), and spring, highlighting its adaptability.

Maize can be grown on a variety of soils, but it performs best on deep, fertile, well-drained loamy and sandy-loam soils that are rich in organic matter. Excellent drainage is critical as the crop cannot tolerate water stagnation for even a few days, which can lead to root death. The ideal soil pH range is from 5.5 to 7.5. A deep soil profile allows for the extensive fibrous root system of maize to anchor firmly and explore a larger volume for nutrients and water.

Maize is a heavy feeder and responds well to fertilizers. For hybrid maize, a general recommendation is 120-150 kg/ha of Nitrogen (N), 60-70 kg/ha of Phosphorus (P₂O₅), and 50-60 kg/ha of Potassium (K₂O). Nitrogen is applied in splits: one-third as basal, one-third at the knee-high stage, and the final third at the pre-tasseling stage to match the crop's demand curve. Phosphorus and Potassium are applied as a basal dose

. Phosphorus and Potassium are applied as a basal dose. Deficiencies of secondary nutrients like Sulphur and micronutrients like Zinc are common and should be corrected based on soil analysis for achieving high yields.

Maize is attacked by several pests and diseases. The most significant recent threat in India is the invasive Fall Armyworm, which voraciously feeds on leaves and whorls. Other key pests include the Maize Stem Borer. Common diseases are Turcicum and Maydis leaf blights, which cause lesions on leaves, and Charcoal Rot, a stalk disease that leads to lodging

. An integrated approach is vital for control, involving the use of resistant hybrids, seed treatment, proper field sanitation, and monitoring with pheromone traps for pests like Fall Armyworm, followed by the application of specific biopesticides or insecticides.

Maize has diverse applications, making it a highly valuable crop. Its primary use globally is as animal feed, especially for poultry and livestock, accounting for over 60% of its consumption. For human food, it is used to make corn flour (makki ka atta), popcorn, cornflakes, and sweet corn. Industrially, it is a key raw material for producing starch, high-fructose corn syrup, corn oil, and biofuel (ethanol). The USA is the world's largest producer
. The USA is the world's largest producer. In India, major producing states include Karnataka, Madhya Pradesh, Bihar, and Telangana.

Tomato is a warm-season crop that thrives in moderate temperatures and requires a long period of bright sunshine. The optimal temperature for fruit set and development is between 21°C and 28°C. It is highly susceptible to frost. Extreme temperatures are detrimental; high temperatures (>35°C) can cause flower drop and poor fruit coloration (reduced lycopene development), while low temperatures inhibit growth
. High humidity combined with warm weather can also increase the incidence of fungal diseases like late blight. It can be grown year-round in southern and western India with proper irrigation.

Tomatoes can be grown in a wide range of soils, from sandy loams to clay, but they perform best in well-drained, deep loamy soils rich in organic matter. Good drainage is crucial to prevent root diseases like bacterial wilt. The ideal soil pH is slightly acidic, between 6.0 and 6.8. Preparing raised beds is a common practice as it improves drainage and aeration in the root zone. The soil should be well-pulverized and enriched with well-decomposed farmyard manure before planting.

Tomatoes are heavy feeders and require a balanced supply of nutrients for high yield and quality. A typical fertilizer dose is 100-120 kg/ha of Nitrogen (N), 60-80 kg/ha of Phosphorus (P₂O₅), and 80-100 kg/ha of Potassium (K₂O). Potassium is particularly important for fruit size, firmness, and taste. A deficiency of Calcium (Ca) can lead to a physiological disorder called Blossom End Rot

. A deficiency of Calcium (Ca) can lead to a physiological disorder called Blossom End Rot. Nitrogen should be applied in split doses to avoid excessive vegetative growth at the expense of fruit production. In modern cultivation, fertigation (applying fertilizers through drip irrigation) is widely used for efficient nutrient delivery.

Tomatoes are vulnerable to many pests and diseases. Major diseases include: Late Blight and Early Blight (fungal), causing spots on leaves and fruit; Bacterial Wilt, which leads to sudden wilting and plant death; and Tomato Leaf Curl Virus (ToLCV), transmitted by whiteflies, which severely stunts plant growth. The most damaging insect pest is the Fruit Borer (*Helicoverpa armigera*), whose larvae bore into the fruit, making them unmarketable
. IPM strategies include using disease-resistant hybrids, proper crop rotation, staking plants to improve air circulation, mulching, and the need-based application of fungicides and insecticides.

Tomatoes are one of the most important vegetable crops globally, consumed both fresh and in processed forms. Fresh tomatoes are used in salads, sandwiches, and as a key ingredient in countless cuisines. The processing industry uses tomatoes to make puree, paste, ketchup, sauces, and canned products. India is the second-largest producer of tomatoes in the world after China. Major production in India comes from Andhra Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Karnataka, and Maharashtra

. Major production in India comes from Andhra Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Karnataka, and Maharashtra. The market is often characterized by high price volatility due to its perishable nature and seasonal production gluts.
